				\begin{document}$${k}_{{{{{{\rm{ET}}}}}}}={V}_{{{{{{\rm{if}}}}}}}^{2}\sqrt{\tfrac{{{{{{\rm{\pi }}}}}}}{{{\lambda }k}_{{{{{{\rm{B}}}}}}}{{{{{{\rm{T}}}}}}\hslash }^{2}}}\,{{\exp }}\left[-\tfrac{{\left(\triangle G+{\lambda }\right)}^{2}}{{4{\lambda }k}_{{{{{{\rm{B}}}}}}}T}\right]$$\end{document}, where λ is the reorganization energy, V represents the electronic coupling between the initial state and the final state, ΔG is the free energy change)29, small reorganization energy facilitate reducing the driving force required for exciton dissociation. Therefore, the reorganization energy plays a crucial role in the photoelectric conversion and the energy loss processes for OSCs.

